<DOCNO>
WSJ900730-0063
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900730-0063.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
07/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   OPEC APPROVED an increase in its minimum reference price
to $21 from $18 a barrel, the first rise in four years. The
figure isn't a set selling price, but rather a goal OPEC
hopes to achieve through production controls. It may be
months before OPEC starts getting the price it wants.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Chemical Banking withdrew as one of five lead banks for
the proposed $4.38 billion buy-out of UAL Corp., according to
people familiar with the plan. Although described as subject
to change, the move is a potentially serious blow to the
buy-out group.
   ---
   Economic growth slowed to a slim 1.2% in the second
quarter, one of the weakest performances in the past 7 1/2
years. Only rising business inventories and higher government
spending kept the economy from contracting.
   ---
   The Senate adopted a $54 billion farm bill, agreeing to
halt the steady decline in farm-income supports. The measure
also gives farmers a freer hand to grow crops they want
without losing their subsidy eligibility.
   ---
   Many banks are cutting back borrowing in the commercial
paper market, as investors grow more nervous about the
banking industry's health.
   ---
   Hong Kong businessman Li Kashing agreed to buy 50% of the
Canadian partnership that bought the huge junk-bond portfolio
of troubled Columbia Savings &amp; Loan Association.
   ---
   The Big Board is set to name William H. Donaldson, a
founder of Donaldson Lufkin, its next chairman, people close
to the exchange said.
   ---
   Machine tool orders rebounded in June from weak May levels
and were 9.1% above June 1989 levels, as durable goods makers
continued to buy machinery to improve productivity.
   ---
   The Social Security surplus shouldn't be counted toward
meeting current deficit-reduction targets, a federal advisory
panel said. The panel also warned against reducing Social
Security taxes as the surplus grows.
   ---
   A Senate panel subpoenaed Robert Thompson, a former aide
to Bush and Reagan, over his role in the 1988 sale of 15
insolvent Texas thrifts. But Mr. Thompson said he won't
appear.
   ---
   Student-lending program changes are being considered by
the administration, including co-signers on loans and credit
checks on borrowers.
   ---
   Liz Claiborne will raise its standard discount to 10% from
8% on shipments of women's apparel to department stores to
boost market share.
   ---
   Turner Broadcasting's loss from the Goodwill Games is
likely to exceed $40 million, including commercial time
Turner must give advertisers as compensation for reaching a
smaller TV audience than promised.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 149,070,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2898.51, off 22.28; transportation 1134.67, off 7.48;
utilities 203.35, up 0.19.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3461.23, up
23.22.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.41, up 0.15; spot
index 132.24, off 0.57.
   Dollar: 149.15 yen, off 1.22; 1.6120 marks, off 0.0125.
</TEXT>
