<HL>
   It's No Use Telling These Jumpy
   Lovers to Look Before You Leap
   ----
   By Sue-Sun Yom
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<LP>
   BASTROP, Texas -- When the Frog went a-courtin', he didn't
risk being squashed flat. But that's what his kissin' cousin,
Bufo Houstonensis, faces here when he feels amorous.
   Now safe sex may be only a hop, skip and a jump away for
this rare and endangered species, otherwise known as Houston
Toads. And it's all because of a bunch of humans who set out
to save some trees.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But we're leaping ahead of our story.
   It seems that at mating time, these lovesick toads seek
the seductive surroundings of local ponds; and that, sadly,
can mean having to cross State Highway 21.
   For a long time, few people here cared about the toads'
risky love life. But last fall, after a rash of accidents
involving cars and trees, the state highway department
proposed cutting down 700 to 1,000 loblolly pines along a
stretch of Highway 21. Soon 50 or 60 angry Bastrop County
residents were hopping on buses to Austin, the state capital,
to protest.
   Although they got the highway department to ax its plan,
the protesters were still suspicious. "Finally we just had to
use this toad thing on them, otherwise they would have done
whatever they wanted," claims Don A. Fries, organizer of
Bastrop's Save the Pines Committee.
   The "toad thing" led to an $18,500 Texas Parks and
Wildlife Department study that turned up six hopping and 12
squashed toads on the highway and concluded that the state
had to do something for the federally protected species.
   The answer: Along with an auto guardrail, the state should
install 28,000 feet of concave, 16-inch-high plastic
"toadrail" to keep the creatures off the roadway, and provide
underground "toad tunnels" to ensure alternate access to
breeding grounds. (Such tunnels can be found in England, but
these just might become America's first toad-tunnels of
love.)
   Now the state is awaiting federal approval of one of two
plans, both of which call for the felling of only 105 trees.
   Andrew H. Price, the state zoologist who wrote the toad
rescue plan, is happy. "There are a number of people who like
toads, including myself," he says. Bastrop residents are
glad, too, because their beloved trees are out of the woods.
   But even now, few here seem sure what a Houston Toad looks
like. "I don't know how they can tell one squashed toad from
another. I've never talked to anybody who's ever seen a
Houston Toad live," confesses Bastrop Mayor David Lock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900730-0038
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900730-0038.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   New Ms. Magazine
   Makes Its Debut,
   Minus Advertising
   ---
   Price Rises but Experts Doubt
   Its Chances of Survival;
   Adding a Literary Flavor
   ----
   By Patrick M. Reilly
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5A
</SO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Defying the skeptics, Ms. magazine -- sans
advertising -- has returned from the dead, but its longevity
is anything but assured.
   The new Ms. emerges today on newsstands and at Waldenbooks
and B. Dalton bookstores nationwide. The premier issue starts
with a bang: a long essay entitled "Sex, Lies &amp; Advertising,"
by Ms. founder Gloria Steinem exploring how women's magazines
shamelessly cater to advertisers. Lang Communications Inc.,
publisher of the feminist magazine, suspended publishing Ms.
in December 1989, after large declines in advertising and
costly attempts by past owners to increase subscribers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   To compensate for its lack of advertising, the new Ms.
must now survive purely on circulation revenue from newsstand
sales and subscribers. On newsstands, its cover price is now
$4.50 -- up from $2.25. Ms.'s annual subscription rate of $40
a year makes it one of the industry's most expensive
magazines. But readers who act immediately can take an
introductory "founding subscriber" rate of $30. Old Ms.
subscribers will be able to pay $25 a year.
   Foregoing advertising allows Chairman Dale Lang to operate
Ms. on a much smaller budget, since the magazine can do
without expensive direct mail campaigns and has no need for a
salaried sales staff. But industry experts continue to
question whether Ms. will find enough readers at the
expensive subscription rate to survive. Only a handful of
successful magazines, such as Consumer Reports, don't accept
advertising.
   Mr. Lang, an entrepreneur who dabbles in television as
well as publishing, last year promised to relaunch the
magazine without advertising and to let the magazine resume
its more vigorous feminist stance, which it had softened in
recent years. Ms., which was founded in 1972, floundered in
the late 1980s as the feminist movement waned and much of the
editorial content of Ms. was imitated by other women's
magazines. The new Ms. boasts a decidedly more literary air:
Its contents include poems, long essays and photojournalism.
   Helped by heavily discounted subscriptions, Ms. had
reached a circulation of 550,000 by its last issue. A Lang
spokeswoman said the magazine can still cover its costs with
fewer than 100,000 subscribers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
